"total":0,"completed":0,"percent_completed":0},"issue_dependencies_summary":{"blocked_by":0,"total_blocked_by":0,"blocking":0,"total_blocking":0},"body":"A mildly naive `__repr__` implementation on some objects leads to confusing results\r\n\r\nSteps to reproduce\r\n==================\r\n\r\nHere is a copy+paste of a simple test case:\r\n```\r\n>>> from rich.style import Style\r\n>>> from rich.text import Span\r\n>>> Span(0,1,'bold')\r\nSpan(0, 1, 'bold')\r\n>>> Span(0,1,Style(bold=True))\r\nSpan(0, 1, 'bold')\r\n>>> Span(0,1,'bold') == Span(0,1,Style(bold=True))\r\nFalse\r\n```\r\n\r\nExpected result\r\n==============\r\n\r\nThe two `Span` objects should compare as equal.\r\n\r\nActual behaviour\r\n================\r\n\r\nThe two `Span` objects compare as unequal, since the `str` and `Style` components are of differing types.\r\n\r\nErrata\r\n=====\r\n\r\n* This is confusing in tests because the `__repr__` method on `Span` objects string-ifies the `Style` component, making them look completely equivalent; the net result is that tests will fail, and the provided diagnostic messages are of negative help.\r\n* The `Span` object was used as an example, but there could be plenty more just like it in the codebase.\r\n","closed_by":{"login":"0xDEC0DE","id":1404587,"node_id":"MDQ6VXNlcjE0MDQ1ODc=","avatar_url":"https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/1404587?v=4","gravatar_id":"","url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE","html_url":"https://github.com/0xDEC0DE","followers_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/0xDEC0DE/repos","events_url":"https://api.gith